<doc id="32337" wikidata="Q741865" url="?curid=32337" title="Uniform continuity">
<text>In mathematics, a real function formula_1 of real numbers is said to be uniformly continuous if there is a positive real number formula_2 such that function values over any function domain interval of the size formula_2 are as close to each other as we want. In other words, for a uniformly continuous real function of real numbers, if we want function value differences to be less than any positive real number formula_4, then there is a positive real number formula_2 such that formula_6 for any formula_7 and formula_8 in any interval of length formula_2 within the domain of formula_1. 

The difference between uniform continuity and (ordinary) continuity is that, in uniform continuity there is a globally applicable formula_2 (the size of a function domain interval over which function value differences are less than formula_4) that depends on only formula_13, while in (ordinary) continuity there is a locally applicable formula_2 that depends on both formula_13 and formula_7. So uniform continuity is a stronger continuity condition than continuity; a function that is uniformly continuous is continuous but a function that is continuous is not necessarily uniformly continuous. The concepts of uniform continuity and continuity can be expanded to functions defined between metric spaces. 

Continuous functions can fail to be uniformly continuous if they are unbounded on a bounded domain, such as formula_17 on formula_18, or if their slopes become unbounded on an infinite domain, such as formula_19 on the real (number) line. However, any Lipschitz map between metric spaces is uniformly continuous, in particular any isometry (distance-preserving map). 

Although continuity can be defined for functions between general topological spaces, defining uniform continuity requires more structure. The concept relies on comparing the sizes of neighbourhoods of distinct points, so it requires a metric space, or more generally a uniform space.

== Definition for functions on metric spaces ==
For a function formula_20 with metric spaces formula_21 and formula_22, the following definitions of uniform continuity and (ordinary) continuity hold.

=== Definition of uniform continuity ===

* formula_1 is called uniformly continuous if for every real number formula_24 there exists a real number formula_25 such that for every formula_26 with formula_27, we have formula_28. The set formula_29 for each formula_30 is a neighbourhood of formula_30 and the set formula_32 for each formula_33 is a neighbourhood of formula_33 by the definition of a neighbourhood in a metric space.
** If formula_35 and formula_36 are subsets of the real line, then formula_37 and formula_38 can be the standard one-dimensional Euclidean distance, yielding the following definition: for every real number formula_24 there exists a real number formula_25 such that for every formula_26, formula_42 (where formula_43 is a material conditional statement saying &quot;if formula_44, then formula_45&quot;).
* Equivalently, formula_1 is said to be uniformly continuous if formula_47. Here quantifications (formula_48, formula_49, formula_50, and formula_51) are used.
* Equivalently, formula_1 is uniformly continuous if it admits a modulus of continuity.

=== Definition of (ordinary) continuity ===

* formula_1 is called continuous formula_54 if for every real number formula_24 there exists a real number formula_25 such that for every formula_57 with formula_27, we have formula_28. The set formula_29 is a neighbourhood of formula_30. Thus, (ordinary) continuity is a local property of the function at the point formula_30.
* Equivalently, a function formula_1 is said to be continuous if formula_64.
* Alternatively, a function formula_1 is said to be continuous if there is a function of all positive real numbers formula_13 and formula_67, formula_68 representing the maximum positive real number, such that at each formula_7 if formula_70 satisfies formula_71 then formula_28. At every formula_7, formula_68 is a monotonically non-decreasing function.

== Local continuity versus global uniform continuity ==
In the definitions, the difference between uniform continuity and continuity is that, in uniform continuity there is a globally applicable formula_2 (the size of a neighbourhood in formula_35 over which values of the metric for function values in formula_36 are less than formula_13) that depends on only formula_13 while in continuity there is a locally applicable formula_2 that depends on the both formula_13 and formula_7. Continuity is a &quot;local&quot; property of a function — that is, a function formula_1 is continuous, or not, at a particular point formula_7 of the function domain formula_85, and this can be determined by looking at only the values of the function in an arbitrarily small neighbourhood of that point. When we speak of a function being continuous on an interval, we mean that the function is continuous at every point of the interval. In contrast, uniform continuity is a &quot;global&quot; property of formula_1, in the sense that the standard definition of uniform continuity refers to every point of formula_85. On the other hand, it is possible to give a definition that is &quot;local&quot; in terms of the natural extension formula_88(the characteristics of which at nonstandard points are determined by the global properties of formula_1), although it is not possible to give a local definition of uniform continuity for an arbitrary hyperreal-valued function, see below.

A mathematical definition that a function formula_1 is continuous on an interval formula_91 and a definition that formula_1 is uniformly continuous on formula_91 are structurally similar as shown in the following.

Continuity of a function formula_94 for metric spaces formula_21 and formula_22 at every point &quot;formula_7&quot; of an interval formula_98 (i.e., continuity of formula_1 on the interval formula_91) is expressed by a formula starting with quantifications
: formula_101,
(metrics formula_102 and formula_103 are formula_104 and formula_105 for formula_106 for the set of real numbers formula_107).

For uniform continuity, the order of the first, second, and third quantifications (formula_108, formula_109, and formula_110) are rotated:
: formula_111.
Thus for continuity on the interval, one takes an arbitrary point formula_7 of the interval&quot;,&quot; and then there must exist a distance formula_2,
: formula_114
while for uniform continuity, a single formula_2 must work uniformly for all points formula_7 of the interval,
: formula_117

== Properties ==

Every uniformly continuous function is continuous, but the converse does not hold. Consider for instance the continuous function formula_118 where formula_119 is the set of real numbers. Given a positive real number formula_13, uniform continuity requires the existence of a positive real number formula_2 such that for all formula_122 with formula_123, we have formula_124. But
: formula_125
and as formula_7 goes to be a higher and higher value, formula_2 needs to be lower and lower to satisfy formula_128 for positive real numbers formula_129 and the given formula_13. This means that there is no specifiable (no matter how small it is) positive real number formula_2 to satisfy the condition for formula_1 to be uniformly continuous so formula_1 is not uniformly continuous.

Any absolutely continuous function (over a compact interval) is uniformly continuous. On the other hand, the Cantor function is uniformly continuous but not absolutely continuous.

The image of a totally bounded subset under a uniformly continuous function is totally bounded. However, the image of a bounded subset of an arbitrary metric space under a uniformly continuous function need not be bounded: as a counterexample, consider the identity function from the integers endowed with the discrete metric to the integers endowed with the usual Euclidean metric.

The Heine–Cantor theorem asserts that &quot;every continuous function on a compact set is uniformly continuous&quot;. In particular, &quot;if a function is continuous on a closed bounded interval of the real line, it is uniformly continuous on that interval&quot;. The Darboux integrability of continuous functions follows almost immediately from this theorem.

If a real-valued function formula_1 is continuous on formula_135 and formula_136 exists (and is finite), then formula_1 is uniformly continuous. In particular, every element of formula_138, the space of continuous functions on formula_119 that vanish at infinity, is uniformly continuous. This is a generalization of the Heine-Cantor theorem mentioned above, since formula_140.

== Examples and nonexamples ==

=== Examples ===
* Linear functions formula_141 are the simplest examples of uniformly continuous functions.
* Any continuous function on the interval formula_142 is also uniformly continuous, since formula_142 is a compact set.
* If a function is differentiable on an open interval and its derivative is bounded, then the function is uniformly continuous on that interval.
* Every Lipschitz continuous map between two metric spaces is uniformly continuous. More generally, every Hölder continuous function is uniformly continuous.
* The absolute value function is uniformly continuous, despite not being differentiable at formula_144. This shows uniformly continuous functions are not always differentiable.
* Despite being nowhere differentiable, the Weierstrass function is uniformly continuous.
* Every member of a uniformly equicontinuous set of functions is uniformly continuous.

=== Nonexamples ===
* Functions that are unbounded on a bounded domain are not uniformly continuous. The tangent function is continuous on the interval formula_145 but is &quot;not&quot; uniformly continuous on that interval, as it goes to infinity as formula_146.
* Functions whose derivative tends to infinity as formula_7 grows large cannot be uniformly continuous. The exponential function formula_148 is continuous everywhere on the real line but is not uniformly continuous on the line, since its derivative is formula_149, and formula_150 as formula_151.

== Visualization ==
For a uniformly continuous function, for every positive real number formula_152 there is a positive real number formula_153 such that two function values formula_154 and formula_155 have the maximum distance formula_13 whenever formula_7 and formula_8 are within the maximum distance formula_2. Thus at each point formula_160 of the graph, if we draw a rectangle with a height slightly less than formula_161 and width a slightly less than formula_162 around that point, then the graph lies completely within the height of the rectangle, i.e., the graph do not pass through the top or the bottom side of the rectangle. For functions that are not uniformly continuous, this isn&#x27;t possible; for these functions, the graph might lie inside the height of the rectangle at some point on the graph but there is a point on the graph where the graph lies above or below the rectangle. (the graph penetrates the top or bottom side of the rectangle.)

== History ==
The first published definition of uniform continuity was by Heine in 1870, and in 1872 he published a proof that a continuous function on an open interval need not be uniformly continuous. The proofs are almost verbatim given by Dirichlet in his lectures on definite integrals in 1854. The definition of uniform continuity appears earlier in the work of Bolzano where he also proved that continuous functions on an open interval do not need to be uniformly continuous. In addition he also states that a continuous function on a closed interval is uniformly continuous, but he does not give a complete proof.

== Other characterizations ==

=== Non-standard analysis ===
In non-standard analysis, a real-valued function &quot;formula_1&quot; of a real variable is microcontinuous at a point &quot;formula_164&quot; precisely if the difference formula_165 is infinitesimal whenever &quot;formula_2&quot; is infinitesimal. Thus &quot;formula_1&quot; is continuous on a set &quot;formula_168&quot; in formula_119 precisely if formula_88 is microcontinuous at every real point formula_171. Uniform continuity can be expressed as the condition that (the natural extension of) formula_1 is microcontinuous not only at real points in formula_168, but at all points in its non-standard counterpart (natural extension) formula_174 in formula_175. Note that there exist hyperreal-valued functions which meet this criterion but are not uniformly continuous, as well as uniformly continuous hyperreal-valued functions which do not meet this criterion, however, such functions cannot be expressed in the form formula_88 for any real-valued function formula_1. (see non-standard calculus for more details and examples).

=== Cauchy continuity ===

For a function between metric spaces, uniform continuity implies Cauchy continuity . More specifically, let formula_168 be a subset of formula_179. If a function formula_180 is uniformly continuous then for every pair of sequences formula_181 and formula_182 such that

