<doc id="32339" wikidata="Q652446" url="?curid=32339" title="Uniform space">
<text>In the mathematical field of topology, a uniform space is a set with additional structure that is used to define &quot;uniform properties&quot;, such as completeness, uniform continuity and uniform convergence. Uniform spaces generalize metric spaces and topological groups, but the concept is designed to formulate the weakest axioms needed for most proofs in analysis.

In addition to the usual properties of a topological structure, in a uniform space one formalizes the notions of relative closeness and closeness of points. In other words, ideas like &quot;&quot;x&quot; is closer to &quot;a&quot; than &quot;y&quot; is to &quot;b&quot;&quot; make sense in uniform spaces. By comparison, in a general topological space, given sets &quot;A,B&quot; it is meaningful to say that a point &quot;x&quot; is &quot;arbitrarily close&quot; to &quot;A&quot; (i.e., in the closure of &quot;A&quot;), or perhaps that &quot;A&quot; is a &quot;smaller neighborhood&quot; of &quot;x&quot; than &quot;B&quot;, but notions of closeness of points and relative closeness are not described well by topological structure alone.

==Definition==
There are three equivalent definitions for a uniform space. They all consist of a space equipped with a uniform structure.

===Entourage definition===

This definition adapts the presentation of a topological space in terms of neighborhood systems. A nonempty collection formula_1 of subsets of formula_2 is a &#x27; (or a &#x27;) if it satisfies the following axioms:
# If formula_3 then formula_4 where formula_5 is the diagonal on formula_6
# If formula_3 and formula_8 then formula_9
# If formula_3 and formula_11 then formula_12
# If formula_3 then there is some formula_14 such that formula_15, where formula_16 denotes the composite of formula_17 with itself. The composite of two subsets formula_17 and formula_19 of formula_2 is defined by formula_21
# If formula_3 then formula_23 where formula_24 is the inverse of formula_25

The non-emptiness of formula_1 taken together with (2) and (3) states that formula_1 is a filter on formula_6 If the last property is omitted we call the space &#x27;. An element formula_19 of formula_1 is called a &#x27; or from the French word for &quot;surroundings&quot;.

One usually writes formula_31 where formula_32 is the vertical cross section of formula_19 and formula_34 is the canonical projection onto the second coordinate. On a graph, a typical entourage is drawn as a blob surrounding the &quot;formula_35&quot; diagonal; all the different formula_36&#x27;s form the vertical cross-sections. If formula_37 then one says that formula_38 and formula_39 are &#x27;. Similarly, if all pairs of points in a subset formula_40 of formula_41 are formula_19-close (that is, if formula_43 is contained in formula_19), formula_40 is called &quot;formula_19-small&quot;. An entourage formula_19 is &#x27; if formula_37 precisely when formula_49 The first axiom states that each point is formula_19-close to itself for each entourage formula_25 The third axiom guarantees that being &quot;both formula_19-close and formula_17-close&quot; is also a closeness relation in the uniformity. The fourth axiom states that for each entourage formula_19 there is an entourage formula_17 that is &quot;not more than half as large&quot;. Finally, the last axiom states that the property &quot;closeness&quot; with respect to a uniform structure is symmetric in formula_38 and formula_57

A &#x27; or &#x27; (or vicinities) of a uniformity formula_1 is any set formula_59 of entourages of formula_1 such that every entourage of formula_1 contains a set belonging to formula_62 Thus, by property 2 above, a fundamental systems of entourages formula_59 is enough to specify the uniformity formula_1 unambiguously: formula_1 is the set of subsets of formula_2 that contain a set of formula_62 Every uniform space has a fundamental system of entourages consisting of symmetric entourages.

Intuition about uniformities is provided by the example of metric spaces: if formula_68 is a metric space, the sets
