form a fundamental system of entourages for the standard uniform structure of formula_70 Then formula_38 and formula_39 are formula_73-close precisely when the distance between formula_38 and formula_39 is at most formula_76

A uniformity formula_1 is &quot;finer&quot; than another uniformity formula_78 on the same set if formula_79 in that case formula_78 is said to be &quot;coarser&quot; than formula_81

===Pseudometrics definition===

Uniform spaces may be defined alternatively and equivalently using systems of pseudometrics, an approach that is particularly useful in functional analysis (with pseudometrics provided by seminorms). More precisely, let formula_82 be a pseudometric on a set formula_70 The inverse images formula_84 for formula_85 can be shown to form a fundamental system of entourages of a uniformity. The uniformity generated by the formula_73 is the uniformity defined by the single pseudometric formula_87 Certain authors call spaces the topology of which is defined in terms of pseudometrics &quot;gauge spaces&quot;.

For a &quot;family&quot; formula_88 of pseudometrics on formula_89 the uniform structure defined by the family is the &quot;least upper bound&quot; of the uniform structures defined by the individual pseudometrics formula_90 A fundamental system of entourages of this uniformity is provided by the set of &quot;finite&quot; intersections of entourages of the uniformities defined by the individual pseudometrics formula_90 If the family of pseudometrics is &quot;finite&quot;, it can be seen that the same uniform structure is defined by a &quot;single&quot; pseudometric, namely the upper envelope formula_92 of the family.

Less trivially, it can be shown that a uniform structure that admits a countable fundamental system of entourages (hence in particular a uniformity defined by a countable family of pseudometrics) can be defined by a single pseudometric. A consequence is that &quot;any&quot; uniform structure can be defined as above by a (possibly uncountable) family of pseudometrics (see Bourbaki: General Topology Chapter IX §1 no. 4).

===Uniform cover definition===

A uniform space formula_93 is a set formula_41 equipped with a distinguished family of coverings formula_95 called &quot;uniform covers&quot;, drawn from the set of coverings of formula_89 that form a filter when ordered by star refinement. One says that a cover formula_97 is a &quot;star refinement&quot; of cover formula_98 written formula_99 if for every formula_100 there is a formula_101 such that if formula_102 then formula_103 Axiomatically, the condition of being a filter reduces to:

# formula_104 is a uniform cover (that is, formula_105).
# If formula_106 with formula_97 a uniform cover and formula_108 a cover of formula_89 then formula_108 is also a uniform cover.
# If formula_97 and formula_108 are uniform covers then there is a uniform cover formula_113 that star-refines both formula_97 and formula_108

Given a point formula_38 and a uniform cover formula_117 one can consider the union of the members of formula_97 that contain formula_38 as a typical neighbourhood of formula_38 of &quot;size&quot; formula_117 and this intuitive measure applies uniformly over the space.

Given a uniform space in the entourage sense, define a cover formula_97 to be uniform if there is some entourage formula_19 such that for each formula_124 there is an formula_125 such that formula_126 These uniform covers form a uniform space as in the second definition. Conversely, given a uniform space in the uniform cover sense, the supersets of formula_127 as formula_97 ranges over the uniform covers, are the entourages for a uniform space as in the first definition. Moreover, these two transformations are inverses of each other. 

==Topology of uniform spaces==

Every uniform space formula_41 becomes a topological space by defining a nonempty subset formula_130 to be open if and only if for every formula_131 there exists an entourage formula_17 such that formula_133 is a subset of formula_134 In this topology, the neighbourhood filter of a point formula_38 is formula_136 This can be proved with a recursive use of the existence of a &quot;half-size&quot; entourage. Compared to a general topological space the existence of the uniform structure makes possible the comparison of sizes of neighbourhoods: formula_133 and formula_138 are considered to be of the &quot;same size&quot;.

The topology defined by a uniform structure is said to be . A uniform structure on a topological space is &quot;compatible&quot; with the topology if the topology defined by the uniform structure coincides with the original topology. In general several different uniform structures can be compatible with a given topology on formula_70

===Uniformizable spaces===

A topological space is called if there is a uniform structure compatible with the topology.

Every uniformizable space is a completely regular topological space. Moreover, for a uniformizable space formula_41 the following are equivalent: 
* formula_41 is a Kolmogorov space
* formula_41 is a Hausdorff space
* formula_41 is a Tychonoff space
* for any compatible uniform structure, the intersection of all entourages is the diagonal formula_144
Some authors (e.g. Engelking) add this last condition directly in the definition of a uniformizable space.

The topology of a uniformizable space is always a symmetric topology; that is, the space is an R0-space.

Conversely, each completely regular space is uniformizable. A uniformity compatible with the topology of a completely regular space formula_41 can be defined as the coarsest uniformity that makes all continuous real-valued functions on formula_41 uniformly continuous. A fundamental system of entourages for this uniformity is provided by all finite intersections of sets formula_147 where formula_148 is a continuous real-valued function on formula_41 and formula_17 is an entourage of the uniform space formula_151 This uniformity defines a topology, which is clearly coarser than the original topology of formula_152 that it is also finer than the original topology (hence coincides with it) is a simple consequence of complete regularity: for any formula_153 and a neighbourhood formula_41 of formula_155 there is a continuous real-valued function formula_148 with formula_157 and equal to 1 in the complement of formula_17

In particular, a compact Hausdorff space is uniformizable. In fact, for a compact Hausdorff space formula_41 the set of all neighbourhoods of the diagonal in formula_2 form the &quot;unique&quot; uniformity compatible with the topology.

A Hausdorff uniform space is metrizable if its uniformity can be defined by a &quot;countable&quot; family of pseudometrics. Indeed, as discussed above, such a uniformity can be defined by a &quot;single&quot; pseudometric, which is necessarily a metric if the space is Hausdorff. In particular, if the topology of a vector space is Hausdorff and definable by a countable family of seminorms, it is metrizable.

==Uniform continuity==
Similar to continuous functions between topological spaces, which preserve topological properties, are the uniformly continuous functions between uniform spaces, which preserve uniform properties. 

A uniformly continuous function is defined as one where inverse images of entourages are again entourages, or equivalently, one where the inverse images of uniform covers are again uniform covers. Explicitly, a function formula_161 between uniform spaces is called if for every entourage formula_17 in formula_163 there exists an entourage formula_19 in formula_41 such that if formula_166 then formula_167 or in other words, whenever formula_17 is an entourage in formula_163 then formula_170 is an entourage in formula_41, where formula_172 is defined by formula_173

All uniformly continuous functions are continuous with respect to the induced topologies. 

Uniform spaces with uniform maps form a category. An isomorphism between uniform spaces is called a ; explicitly, it is a uniformly continuous bijection whose inverse is also uniformly continuous. 
A is an injective uniformly continuous map formula_174 between uniform spaces whose inverse formula_175 is also uniformly continuous, where the image formula_176 has the subspace uniformity inherited from formula_177

==Completeness==

Generalizing the notion of complete metric space, one can also define completeness for uniform spaces. Instead of working with Cauchy sequences, one works with Cauchy filters (or Cauchy nets).

A &#x27; (respectively, a &#x27;) formula_178 on a uniform space formula_41 is a filter (respectively, a prefilter) formula_178 such that for every entourage formula_181 there exists formula_182 with formula_183 In other words, a filter is Cauchy if it contains &quot;arbitrarily small&quot; sets. It follows from the definitions that each filter that converges (with respect to the topology defined by the uniform structure) is a Cauchy filter.
A is a Cauchy filter that does not contain any smaller (that is, coarser) Cauchy filter (other than itself). It can be shown that every Cauchy filter contains a unique . The neighbourhood filter of each point (the filter consisting of all neighbourhoods of the point) is a minimal Cauchy filter.

Conversely, a uniform space is called if every Cauchy filter converges. Any compact Hausdorff space is a complete uniform space with respect to the unique uniformity compatible with the topology.

Complete uniform spaces enjoy the following important property: if formula_184 is a &quot;uniformly continuous&quot; function from a &quot;dense&quot; subset formula_40 of a uniform space formula_41 into a &quot;complete&quot; uniform space formula_187 then formula_148 can be extended (uniquely) into a uniformly continuous function on all of formula_70

A topological space that can be made into a complete uniform space, whose uniformity induces the original topology, is called a completely uniformizable space.

A formula_41 is a pair formula_191 consisting of a complete uniform space formula_192 and a uniform embedding formula_193 whose image formula_176 is a dense subset of formula_195 

===Hausdorff completion of a uniform space===

As with metric spaces, every uniform space formula_41 has a : that is, there exists a complete Hausdorff uniform space formula_163 and a uniformly continuous map formula_174 (if formula_41 is a Hausdorff uniform space then formula_200 is a topological embedding) with the following property:

: for any uniformly continuous mapping formula_148 of formula_41 into a complete Hausdorff uniform space formula_203 there is a unique uniformly continuous map formula_204 such that formula_205

The Hausdorff completion formula_163 is unique up to isomorphism. As a set, formula_163 can be taken to consist of the Cauchy filters on formula_70 As the neighbourhood filter formula_209 of each point formula_38 in formula_41 is a minimal Cauchy filter, the map formula_200 can be defined by mapping formula_38 to formula_214 The map formula_200 thus defined is in general not injective; in fact, the graph of the equivalence relation formula_216 is the intersection of all entourages of formula_89 and thus formula_200 is injective precisely when formula_41 is Hausdorff.

The uniform structure on formula_163 is defined as follows: for each formula_17 (that is, such that formula_222 implies formula_223), let formula_224 be the set of all pairs formula_225 of minimal Cauchy filters &quot;which have in common at least one formula_17-small set&quot;. The sets formula_224 can be shown to form a fundamental system of entourages; formula_163 is equipped with the uniform structure thus defined.

The set formula_176 is then a dense subset of formula_177 If formula_41 is Hausdorff, then formula_200 is an isomorphism onto formula_233 and thus formula_41 can be identified with a dense subset of its completion. Moreover, formula_176 is always Hausdorff; it is called the If formula_236 denotes the equivalence relation formula_237 then the quotient space formula_238 is homeomorphic to formula_239

==Examples==

# Every metric space formula_240 can be considered as a uniform space. Indeed, since a metric is &quot;a fortiori&quot; a pseudometric, the pseudometric definition furnishes formula_241 with a uniform structure. A fundamental system of entourages of this uniformity is provided by the setsformula_242This uniform structure on formula_241 generates the usual metric space topology on formula_244 However, different metric spaces can have the same uniform structure (trivial example is provided by a constant multiple of a metric). This uniform structure produces also equivalent definitions of uniform continuity and completeness for metric spaces.
# Using metrics, a simple example of distinct uniform structures with coinciding topologies can be constructed. For instance, let formula_245 be the usual metric on formula_246 and let formula_247 Then both metrics induce the usual topology on formula_248 yet the uniform structures are distinct, since formula_249 is an entourage in the uniform structure for formula_250 but not for formula_251 Informally, this example can be seen as taking the usual uniformity and distorting it through the action of a continuous yet non-uniformly continuous function.
# Every topological group formula_252 (in particular, every topological vector space) becomes a uniform space if we define a subset formula_253 to be an entourage if and only if it contains the set formula_254 for some neighborhood formula_19 of the identity element of formula_256 This uniform structure on formula_252 is called the &quot;right uniformity&quot; on formula_258 because for every formula_259 the right multiplication formula_260 is uniformly continuous with respect to this uniform structure. One may also define a left uniformity on formula_261 the two need not coincide, but they both generate the given topology on formula_256
# For every topological group formula_252 and its subgroup formula_264 the set of left cosets formula_265 is a uniform space with respect to the uniformity formula_1 defined as follows. The sets formula_267 where formula_19 runs over neighborhoods of the identity in formula_258 form a fundamental system of entourages for the uniformity formula_81 The corresponding induced topology on formula_265 is equal to the quotient topology defined by the natural map formula_272
# The trivial topology belongs to a uniform space in which the whole cartesian product formula_2 is the only entourage.

==History==

Before André Weil gave the first explicit definition of a uniform structure in 1937, uniform concepts, like completeness, were discussed using metric spaces. Nicolas Bourbaki provided the definition of uniform structure in terms of entourages in the book &quot;Topologie Générale&quot; and John Tukey gave the uniform cover definition. Weil also characterized uniform spaces in terms of a family of pseudometrics.

